   <font class="ArticleSource"><big>News Roundup:</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleHead"><big>Funny and Sad at the Same Time</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </font><font class="ArticleAuthor">Kohath</font>
   <div align="right">
   <font class="ArticleTime">01/23/2002 08:59 PM CST &nbsp;&nbsp; 3 Comments</font>
   <div align="left">
   <font class="ArticleText"><big>Ensnared by Necromancer Angst</big><p>Absor learned a thing or two in the past few days.  <i>Necromancers are never happy</i> is one of the fundamental facts of Everquest life, and attending to them simply tends to focus their unhappiness on you.  <p>A Ranger followed up on Absor's Insidious Retrogression comments with a correction:<p><b><small>Absor said &quot;That's how snare components work. Nothing new about the way this spell works. Multi-effect spells do tend to break earlier.&quot;<p>Just a correction, that's not how snare components work. Snare spells have a set duration, they don't have a resist check each tick like root lines. The druid and wizard snare lines both work this way, as does the necro darkness line and druid and necro epics. <p>The only one that checks each tick is Tangling Weeds, and that is to balance the near instant cast. (Of course it's worthless now with the 7 second recast due to how often it is resisted, but that is another subject).<p>Elindel<br>60 Ranger<br>Bristlebane</small></b><p>To which Absor said: <p><i><small>Multi-component spells (even Snare spells) check to see if they break at regular intervals. Most spells with a Snare component have been specially coded to bypass that check. Some have noted that, for example, the Necromancer epic weapon effect worked the same way until it was given special coding to change that.</small></i><p>Then he said they'd look into it.  Somehow, I don't think that will make the Necromancers any happier.<p>That exchange was followed up with more talk of Chill Bones and Ignite Bones.  A player asked <i>if changing a dragon into a skeleton makes Dragon Bane fail, shouldn't it then make vs.-Undead spells succeed?</i>  (I wonder if this question was posted from the back room at The Android's Dungeon.)  <b>Absor didn't know.</b><p>It's because it's <i>magic</i> Absor.  That mystical mojo <b>defies the rules of logic</b>.  Also, it probably has something to do with the way that the skeleton illusion of the spell doesn't change the type of the monster to &quot;Undead&quot; in the server's data structure, but it does change the data that determines whether Dragon Bane hits -- probably the which-model-do-I-display field.  Some sort of high-level magical researcher or low-level game programmer can probably track that down for you.  The ultimate solution to this problem is clear: drink three beers.<p><big>Comedy or Tragedy: You be the Judge</big><p>A clever writer of dry satire or a downtrodden victim of cruel circumstance aired his misfortune on many of the most popular EverQuest boards today.  His post a long one, so I won't quote it here.  Read it on the Safehouse.  It's entitled <a href="http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showMessage?topicID=21884.topic">This is outrageous. I am speechless</a>.<p>Sorry to hear about the trouble.<p><big>All Your Base Are Belong To Us!</big><p>The maker of the <a href="http://www.lineagethebloodpledge.com/">world's most popular and most profitable online game</a>, <a href="http://www.ncsoft.co.kr/">NCSoft of South Korea</a>, has teamed up with the comparatively modest Sony Online Entertainment (Verant) to bring EverQuest to Korea and the Asian market.  The <a href="http://www.verant.com/press/soe_ncsoft012302.html">press release</a> can be found on the Verant Corporate website.<p>This is a smart move for Verant.  NCSoft has <b>more than 22 million</b> players for Lineage (which, incidentally, I've heard is no fun, and is <a href="http://www.lineage-us.com/mac/">soon to be available for the Macintosh</a>).  This partnership should provide a significant head-start for Verant in Asia, while providing NCSoft's customers a first-person perspective MMOG for the first time.<p><big>The cane, it's plain, drops mainly off the Dain</big><p>A reader sent us a covert tip about a very confidential new development within the Coldain royal family.  It's all very <i>hush-hush</i> -- it's so confidential, in fact, that it may not be true at all.  <p>The Dain has reportedly <a href="http://www.clubfu.com/">been seen</a> in a compromising position with a new weapon.  The <a href="http://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/item.html?item=6090">Sceptre of Destruction</a> has heretofore only been found in the Sleeper's Tomb.<p>Has the Dain been leading a double life?  Where does he go when he's not in Icewell keep?  Is Rosie O'Donnell pregnant with Dain Frostreaver's baby, or is she just fat?  We don't know the answers, but when we find out, the scandal will shake the very foundations of Thurgadin.  For now, it's <A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0790734850/mobhunter-20">strictly on the Q-T</a>.<p><big>Ragefire</big><p><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000465.html">Absor also said some stuff about Ragefire</a>.  Clerics, read.  Everyone else, nevermind.<p><big>This is the End</big><p>And with that, Absor was gone.<p><b><small>I'll be gone for the rest of the week. I hope to meet a bunch of you in Dallas this weekend.<p>Keep sending in comments, the team will still be reading them.<p>Have a safe week.<p>Alan</small></b><p>Yeah, we'll be safe.  Can you announce some new stuff at the Fan Faire so there's some interesting news?  Thanks in advance.</font>
  </td>
 </tr>
